# Version 2.0.5
[Chore] Releases are now built by GitHub Actions for Windows, Linux and macOS. The workflow is started
        by hand from the Actions tab and has no push, pull request or tag trigger, so an ordinary commit
        never builds or publishes anything. It runs the test suite on all three platforms, builds the
        .msi and portable .zip, an AppImage and a .dmg, and attaches them to a release whose notes come
        from this file. See docs/RELEASING.md.

[Fix] Building from a clean checkout works again. build and package passed --update unconditionally,
      which fails when there is no bundle to update yet, so the very first build in a fresh clone died.
      The bundle is now created as its own step when it is missing, and --update is still used
      afterwards so a rebuild cannot ship stale sources.

[Fix] Translations can be compiled without GNU gettext installed, falling back to babel, which is a
      pure Python implementation. msgfmt is still preferred when present. This removes the last piece
      of the build that needed a system package installed differently on each operating system.

[Fix] requirements.txt was missing pytest and so could not run the test suite it is meant to set up.

[Feature] The About Program window now actually introduces the program. Its first tab shows the
          application icon, the program name, the version, a clickable link to the project and a short
          description of what the tool is for. The GNU GPL text that used to fill this tab moved to a
          new tab of its own, named "License", which sits directly after it and ahead of the
          third party licenses.
[Feature] The name, version and URL shown there are read from the packaging metadata at runtime, with
          pyproject.toml as a fallback when running from a source checkout. Nothing is duplicated in
          the source, so the About window cannot drift out of step with what was actually built. A
          test asserts the reported version matches pyproject.toml.

# Version 2.0.4
[Feature] The "Send on Startup" tab can now create Home Assistant entities automatically, using MQTT
          auto discovery. Three columns were added: HA Entity, HA ID and HA Name. When HA ID is filled
          in, a retained discovery message is published to homeassistant/<HA Entity>/<HA ID>/config
          carrying {"name": <HA Name>, "state_topic": <Topic>, "unique_id": <HA ID>}, immediately
          before the row's own message. Home Assistant creates the entity on the spot, with no YAML
          and no restart.
[Feature] HA Entity defaults to "sensor" and is an editable drop down offering the most common
          components, so anything Home Assistant supports can still be typed in. HA Name falls back to
          the HA ID when left blank, so an entity is never left unnamed.
[Feature] Rows with an empty HA ID are published exactly as before, with no discovery message. This is
          also what happens to every configuration written by an earlier version, so upgrading changes
          nothing until the new columns are filled in.

[Note] Discovery messages are always sent retained, regardless of the row's own Retain setting,
       because Home Assistant forgets entities whose discovery message is not retained.

[Note] Removing a row stops the entity being announced, but does not remove it from Home Assistant,
       since the retained discovery message stays on the broker. To delete an entity, add a row that
       publishes an empty payload with Retain ticked to that same .../config topic, leaving HA ID
       blank, and start the program once.

[Fix] HA Entity and HA ID are validated before use. Both become topic levels, so a value containing a
      slash, a wildcard or a space would produce a broken discovery topic. Such a row is reported in
      the Logs tab and skipped for discovery only; its own message is still published.

# Version 2.0.3
[Feature] New "Send on Startup" tab. It lists MQTT messages that are published once a connection to
          the broker has been established, before the program starts listening. Each row has a Topic,
          a Payload, a QoS level and a Retain flag. Leave the tab empty and the program behaves
          exactly as before. The intended use is letting each desktop configure its own entities in
          Home Assistant whenever it comes online.
[Feature] Startup messages are stored in their own configuration file, default-startup-messages.json,
          next to the existing settings and payload files, and honour portable mode. A matching
          --startup-configuration-file command line option was added for symmetry with the other two.
[Feature] Topics on this tab are absolute. They are deliberately not prefixed with the topic from the
          Connection tab, because the point is to address other devices' entities rather than the
          program's own subscription tree.

[Note] The messages are sent on every successful connection, not only on the very first one. This
       means they are re-sent after a reconnect, which is what you want when a broker restart has
       lost the retained state that Home Assistant relies on. Every send is written to the Logs tab.

[Fix] The main window now opens wide enough to show all of its tabs. The default width is a quarter
      of the screen, which a fourth tab no longer fits into, so the tab bar collapsed into scroll
      arrows. The window asks the tab bar how much room it needs, which also covers longer labels in
      translated builds.

[Fix] Tab positions are no longer hardcoded as indices. Jumping to the Logs or Connection tab, and
      marking a tab as having unsaved changes, now look the tab up by widget. The old code addressed
      tabs by number and would have silently acted on the wrong tab once a fourth one was inserted.
[Feature] New Windows build artifact: a portable .zip, built with "python tasks.py package-portable"
          (or "make package-portable") and written to dist/ alongside the .msi. It unpacks to a single
          folder containing the executable and a ready-made "data" folder, so unzipping it anywhere and
          running the .exe gives a completely self-contained install that touches nothing outside its
          own folder. The data folder ships with a short readme in it, both to explain itself and so
          that archive tools which discard empty folders cannot break portable mode on extraction.
[Feature] Automatic portable mode. On startup the app looks for a directory named "data" next to the
          executable. If one is there, every runtime file (settings, payload handlers and the
          temporary certificate .pem) is read from and written to that directory, exactly as if
          --mqtt-configuration-file and --payload-configuration-file had been passed. If there is no
          such directory the app behaves as before and uses the per-user location
          (%appdata%\easy-mqtt-handler on Windows, ~/.config/easy-mqtt-handler elsewhere).
          The directory is never created automatically: its presence is the opt-in, so creating it
          would silently and permanently switch the user over. A plain file named "data" is ignored.
          Explicit command line options still take precedence over portable mode.

[Fix] Configuration files are now read as UTF-8 and tolerate a byte order mark, and are written as
      UTF-8 rather than in the system's local codepage. Portable mode puts these files right next to
      the executable where they are much more likely to be hand-edited, and several Windows editors
      add a BOM when saving, which previously made the file fail to load.

[Fix] The main window is shown on first run again when portable mode is active. First run was
      previously inferred from having just created the config directory, which never happens in
      portable mode because the "data" directory must already exist to be detected. It is now
      inferred from the absence of a settings file, which is correct in both modes.

# Version 2.0.1
[Feature] The GUI now follows the operating system's light/dark preference on Windows, macOS and
          Linux. Qt5 does not do this by itself on Windows, which is why the app stayed light there
          even with the system set to dark; on Linux the platform theme plugin already handled it.
          The app only overrides the palette when the platform has not already produced one matching
          the system preference, so the native look is preserved wherever it was already correct.
[Feature] The colour scheme is re-checked while the app runs, so toggling the OS setting updates the
          window without a restart. Qt5 emits no signal for this on Windows, so it is polled.
[Feature] On Windows the native title bar is switched to its dark variant via DWM, which Qt5 does not
          do on its own. Note that Windows ignores this for the active window when "Show accent colour
          on title bars and window borders" is enabled in Personalisation, in which case the accent
          colour wins; that is Windows' own precedence rule, not a limitation of the app.
[Feature] The theme can be forced with the EASY_MQTT_HANDLER_THEME environment variable, set to
          either "dark" or "light", which overrides detection. Useful for testing and for desktops
          whose preference cannot be detected.

[Fix] Corrected the paths of the four BUTTON_* icon constants, which pointed at assets/button/
      instead of assets/buttons/. These constants are currently unused, so nothing was visibly
      broken; a test now verifies that every icon path resolves to a real file.

# Version 2.0.0
First release of Easy MQTT Handler 2, a fork and continuation of Easy MQTT Handler by A. Zeil.
No user-facing behaviour was changed in this release; the work was on project identity,
the build system, tests and cross-platform support.

[Chore] Rebranded as "Easy MQTT Handler 2": new bundle identifier (com.atmanactive), project URL and
        maintainer. The bundle ID change means this fork installs alongside the original instead of
        colliding with it. Original authorship and the GPLv3+ licence are unchanged.
[Chore] Verified the app builds, packages and runs on Python 3.14; no source changes were required.
[Chore] Declared the licence as license.file per PEP 621, silencing a briefcase deprecation warning.
[Chore] Added .briefcase/, logs/, dist-info/ and .pytest_cache/ to .gitignore; these build byproducts
        were previously left untracked in the working tree.
[Chore] Pointed the license-load error message at this fork's repository instead of upstream's.

[Feature] Replaced the Makefile and the four src/scripts/*.sh helpers with tasks.py, a single task
          runner using only the standard library that behaves identically on Windows, Linux and macOS.
          Run "python tasks.py --help" for the task list. The Makefile is kept as a thin wrapper so
          existing "make" targets, including activate-venv, still work on Linux and macOS.
[Feature] Translations can now be generated and compiled on Windows. Template generation moved from
          pygettext3 to xgettext, and source references in .pot files use posix separators so
          regenerating them on different platforms no longer churns the diff.
[Feature] Added a test suite (tests/) with 14 tests covering the Utils helpers and the JSON-backed
          settings and payload stores. Runs via "pytest", "python tasks.py test", or
          "briefcase dev --test".

[Fix] The build no longer ships untranslated. Compiled .mo files are generated artifacts kept out of
      git, and briefcase copies app sources only when the bundle is created, so a build from a fresh
      clone silently fell back to the English source strings. tasks.py now compiles missing
      translations before building and passes --update so the result is copied into the bundle.
[Fix] translation-compile-mos.sh tested msgfmt's standard output rather than its exit status, and an
      empty string compares equal to zero in bash, so it reported success even when compilation
      failed. The replacement checks exit codes on every external command.
[Fix] Closed three leaked file handles: MQTTSettings.load_settings, MQTTPayloads.load_payload_data
      and Utils.load_license_file each opened a file without closing it. ResourceWarnings are now
      fatal in the test suite to keep them from returning.
[Fix] Icon regeneration no longer misidentifies the Windows FAT-to-NTFS utility (System32\convert.exe)
      as ImageMagick; the candidate binary is verified before use.

[Docs] Documented tasks.py as the entry point for builds, tests and translations across BUILDING.md,
       I18N.md, ICONS.md and REPO-STRUCTURE.md, and removed references to the deleted shell scripts.
       I18N.md no longer warns that translating only works on Linux.
[Docs] Documented the GNU gettext requirement (xgettext and msgfmt) with install commands per platform,
       and noted that the macOS .icns step needs icnsutils, which is packaged for Linux only.

